INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (1,0,'2023-07-23 21:35:37','2023-07-23 21:35:37','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">WELCOME TO MONK: THE MOBILE MAGAZINE.</p>\n<br><br>\n<p>Monk began in April 1986 when Mike, Jim, and their neurotic cat Nurse loaded up their worldly possessions, including sundry wool sweaters, into a rented U-Haul and fled San Francisco because they couldn’t afford the rent.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>They landed on John Deming’s back lawn in Paradise, California.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>After being mistakenly hired as “gardeners” for two months, they earned enough scratch to purchase their first vehicle, the beloved “72 Ford Econoline van,” from which they began compiling a newsletter dubbed “The Monthly Monk.”<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>Their purpose was to stay in touch with friends and family while not looking like a couple of sleazy bums wandering through America.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>Only three months into the journey, all hell broke loose, and they were up to their ears in “growing subscriber interest.”<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>Their “monthly” newsletter, already three months late, was wisely renamed Monk: The “Try-Quarterly.”<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>They would “try” to come out quarterly.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>As The Monks traveled throughout the Lower 48, Monk took on a power of its own.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>By March 1987, it went national, becoming the world’s first mobile magazine, supported by courageous advertisers and a devoted public.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>The Monks set a new goal of searching the entire continent for their lost cat Nurse.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\"> </span></p>\n<p><span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span></p>\n<p>Monk was written from the road about life on the road.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>In each issue, The Monks described their latest encounters with the lucky victims of their latest pitstop: everyone from artists to housewives, clowns to visionaries, and occasionally, even real live monks.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>They were a gentle tickle in the side of the earnest seeker, the frazzled clerk, and the burned-out healer.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>They sought out the inner child, goofball, and prankster in all of us, though they could be quite informative, offering a uniquely personal yet keenly researched take on the land and its people.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>They were also useful.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>Thousands of readers used Monk to teach dogs how to fetch.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>But the magazine was just the hard incarnation of a more expansive vision: The Monks’ living cells interacting with each other, the planet, and the sentient beings they met along the way.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>They were a traveling show, publishing house, and monastery all rolled into one.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>Only through Monk could you not only vicariously live through their escapades but join The Monks for the drive.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>And many did.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\"> </span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Now, nearly 25 years since its last print issue, Monk has grown far beyond a rare and treasured heirloom.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>It has entered mythic status as evidence of a pre-Internet America few today have experienced.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>As resident in-house philosopher Jim Monk recently opined, “Monk was pre-digital, fully human, non-AI.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>It was imperfect, roughhewn, real.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>You had to have it postal mailed to you or quickly grab it on a newsstand before it sold out.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>As today\'s billionaire CEOs sing the praises of their computer-engineered ‘content solutions,’ in truth, they’ve lost the connection to what is truly human and good.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>With the mid-90s Faustian bargain that came with the Internet and the rise of a dehumanized, dopamine-driven techno-sphere, the hunger for a slower, kinder, pre-digital connection only grew apace.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>Smartphones, smartwatches, game consoles, social media, and search engines are now so interwoven into our lives that we are, in effect, ‘bowling alone.’<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>Lots of sugar, no nutrition.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>Monk is the antidote to all that.”<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\"> </span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>If you still hunger for the authentic amateur and the real America, we invite you to, at long last, buy your untouched Monk back issues here.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>And please drop us a line to let us know who you are, where you are, and what’s been going on. </p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>To fans and friends old and new . . . The Journey Continues.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Read This','Before the worldwide web, smarty phones, GPS, Tik-tokery, and selfies, there was Monk––a singular, self-published print magazine, written, published, and distributed over twelve years entirely from the road.  Here are the basic facts, as we currently remember them. <br><br>\n\n\nThe Year: 1986.<br>\nThe Vehicle: a 1972 Ford Econoline Van.<br> \nThe Founders: James Crotty, Michael Lane, and their cat Nurse.<br> \nThe Tools: The first Apple Macintosh computer, piles of floppy disks, and an Olympus point-and-shoot camera.<br> \nThe Project: Twelve solid years traversing North America <br> \nThe Readers: millions of wannabe Monks and Monkettes living vicariously through the madcap adventures of their trusted compadres, The Monks.<br> \nThe Motto: Simple, Mobile, True.<br> \nThe Monikers: Kerou-wacky, Travel with a Twist, a magazine with a heart. <br> \nThe Achievements: invented dashboard publishing, helped pioneer the mobile office and the zine, created blogging and van life before either were a thing. <br> <br> \n\nAccept no substitutes. Monk is the you you’ve been waiting for. Here’s how each issue of Monk began (with slight variations as we moved forward in space and time).\n','publish','open','open','','read-this','','','2023-07-23 21:35:37','2023-07-23 21:35:37','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?p=1',0,'post','',1),(2,1,'2023-07-23 21:35:37','2023-07-23 21:35:37','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is an example page. It\'s different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p>Hi there! I\'m a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my website. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like pi&#241;a coladas. (And gettin\' caught in the rain.)</p></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>...or something like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p>The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.</p></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a new WordPress user, you should go to <a href=\"http://monkmagazine.test/wp/wp-admin/\">your dashboard</a> to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Sample Page','','trash','closed','open','','sample-page__trashed','','','2023-09-10 07:11:42','2023-09-10 07:11:42','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?page_id=2',0,'page','',0),(3,1,'2023-07-23 21:35:37','2023-07-23 21:35:37','<!-- wp:heading --><h2>Who we are</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>Our website address is: http://monkmagazine.test.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Comments</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>When visitors leave comments on the site we collect the data shown in the comments form, and also the visitor&#8217;s IP address and browser user agent string to help spam detection.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>An anonymized string created from your email address (also called a hash) may be provided to the Gravatar service to see if you are using it. The Gravatar service privacy policy is available here: https://automattic.com/privacy/. After approval of your comment, your profile picture is visible to the public in the context of your comment.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Media</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you upload images to the website, you should avoid uploading images with embedded location data (EXIF GPS) included. Visitors to the website can download and extract any location data from images on the website.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Cookies</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you leave a comment on our site you may opt-in to saving your name, email address and website in cookies. These are for your convenience so that you do not have to fill in your details again when you leave another comment. These cookies will last for one year.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>If you visit our login page, we will set a temporary cookie to determine if your browser accepts cookies. This cookie contains no personal data and is discarded when you close your browser.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>When you log in, we will also set up several cookies to save your login information and your screen display choices. Login cookies last for two days, and screen options cookies last for a year. If you select &quot;Remember Me&quot;, your login will persist for two weeks. If you log out of your account, the login cookies will be removed.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>If you edit or publish an article, an additional cookie will be saved in your browser. This cookie includes no personal data and simply indicates the post ID of the article you just edited. It expires after 1 day.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Embedded content from other websites</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>Articles on this site may include embedded content (e.g. videos, images, articles, etc.). Embedded content from other websites behaves in the exact same way as if the visitor has visited the other website.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>These websites may collect data about you, use cookies, embed additional third-party tracking, and monitor your interaction with that embedded content, including tracking your interaction with the embedded content if you have an account and are logged in to that website.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Who we share your data with</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you request a password reset, your IP address will be included in the reset email.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>How long we retain your data</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you leave a comment, the comment and its metadata are retained indefinitely. This is so we can recognize and approve any follow-up comments automatically instead of holding them in a moderation queue.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>For users that register on our website (if any), we also store the personal information they provide in their user profile. All users can see, edit, or delete their personal information at any time (except they cannot change their username). Website administrators can also see and edit that information.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>What rights you have over your data</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you have an account on this site, or have left comments, you can request to receive an exported file of the personal data we hold about you, including any data you have provided to us. You can also request that we erase any personal data we hold about you. This does not include any data we are obliged to keep for administrative, legal, or security purposes.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Where your data is sent</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>Visitor comments may be checked through an automated spam detection service.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Privacy Policy','','draft','closed','open','','privacy-policy','','','2023-07-23 21:35:37','2023-07-23 21:35:37','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?page_id=3',0,'page','',0),(5,1,'2023-07-23 21:37:52','2023-07-23 21:37:52','{\"version\": 2, \"isGlobalStylesUserThemeJSON\": true }','Custom Styles','','publish','closed','closed','','wp-global-styles-twentytwentythree','','','2023-07-23 21:37:52','2023-07-23 21:37:52','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/index.php/2023/07/23/wp-global-styles-twentytwentythree/',0,'wp_global_styles','',0),(6,1,'2023-07-23 21:38:10','2023-07-23 21:38:10','<!-- wp:template-part {\"slug\":\"header\",\"theme\":\"twentytwentythree\",\"tagName\":\"header\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"tagName\":\"main\",\"style\":{\"spacing\":{\"margin\":{\"top\":\"var:preset|spacing|50\",\"bottom\":\"var:preset|spacing|70\"}}},\"layout\":{\"type\":\"constrained\"}} -->\n<main class=\"wp-block-group\" style=\"margin-top:var(--wp--preset--spacing--50);margin-bottom:var(--wp--preset--spacing--70)\"><!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1,\"align\":\"wide\",\"style\":{\"spacing\":{\"margin\":{\"bottom\":\"var:preset|spacing|60\"}}}} -->\n<h1 class=\"wp-block-heading alignwide\" style=\"margin-bottom:var(--wp--preset--spacing--60)\">Simple. Mobile. True.</h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:query {\"queryId\":0,\"query\":{\"perPage\":3,\"pages\":0,\"offset\":0,\"postType\":\"post\",\"order\":\"desc\",\"orderBy\":\"date\",\"author\":\"\",\"search\":\"\",\"exclude\":[],\"sticky\":\"\",\"inherit\":true},\"displayLayout\":{\"type\":\"flex\",\"columns\":3},\"align\":\"wide\",\"layout\":{\"type\":\"constrained\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-query alignwide\"><!-- wp:post-template {\"align\":\"wide\"} -->\n<!-- wp:post-featured-image {\"isLink\":true,\"width\":\"100%\",\"height\":\"max(15vw, 30vh)\",\"align\":\"wide\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:post-title {\"isLink\":true} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:post-excerpt /-->\n\n<!-- wp:post-date {\"isLink\":true} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":\"var(\\u002d\\u002dwp\\u002d\\u002dpreset\\u002d\\u002dspacing\\u002d\\u002d40)\"} -->\n<div style=\"height:var(--wp--preset--spacing--40)\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n<!-- /wp:post-template -->\n\n<!-- wp:query-pagination {\"paginationArrow\":\"arrow\",\"align\":\"wide\",\"layout\":{\"type\":\"flex\",\"justifyContent\":\"space-between\"}} -->\n<!-- wp:query-pagination-previous {\"label\":\"Newer Posts\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:query-pagination-next {\"label\":\"Older Posts\"} /-->\n<!-- /wp:query-pagination --></div>\n<!-- /wp:query -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":\"var(\\u002d\\u002dwp\\u002d\\u002dpreset\\u002d\\u002dspacing\\u002d\\u002d60)\"} -->\n<div style=\"height:var(--wp--preset--spacing--60)\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:columns {\"align\":\"wide\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns alignwide\"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"1.2\"}},\"fontSize\":\"x-large\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-x-large-font-size\" style=\"line-height:1.2\">Got any book recommendations?		</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button {\"fontSize\":\"small\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\">\n				Get In Touch				</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"><!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns --></main>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:template-part {\"slug\":\"footer\",\"theme\":\"twentytwentythree\",\"tagName\":\"footer\"} /-->','Home','Displays the latest posts as either the site homepage or a custom page defined under reading settings. If it exists, the Front Page template overrides this template when posts are shown on the front page.','publish','closed','closed','','home','','','2023-07-23 21:38:10','2023-07-23 21:38:10','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/index.php/2023/07/23/home/',0,'wp_template','',0),(8,1,'2023-07-23 21:39:44','2023-07-23 21:39:44','','Shop','','publish','closed','closed','','shop','','','2023-07-23 21:39:44','2023-07-23 21:39:44','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/index.php/shop/',0,'page','',0),(9,1,'2023-07-23 21:39:44','2023-07-23 21:39:44','<!-- wp:shortcode -->[woocommerce_cart]<!-- /wp:shortcode -->','Cart','','publish','closed','closed','','cart','','','2023-07-23 21:39:44','2023-07-23 21:39:44','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/index.php/cart/',0,'page','',0),(10,1,'2023-07-23 21:39:44','2023-07-23 21:39:44','<!-- wp:shortcode -->[woocommerce_checkout]<!-- /wp:shortcode -->','Checkout','','publish','closed','closed','','checkout','','','2023-07-23 21:39:44','2023-07-23 21:39:44','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/index.php/checkout/',0,'page','',0),(11,1,'2023-07-23 21:39:44','2023-07-23 21:39:44','<!-- wp:shortcode -->\r\n<p>[woocommerce_my_account]</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:shortcode -->','My Account','','publish','closed','closed','','my-account','','','2023-09-10 07:11:51','2023-09-10 07:11:51','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/index.php/my-account/',0,'page','',0),(12,1,'2023-07-23 21:39:44','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><b>This is a sample page.</b></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<h3>Overview</h3>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our refund and returns policy lasts 30 days. If 30 days have passed since your purchase, we can’t offer you a full refund or exchange.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To be eligible for a return, your item must be unused and in the same condition that you received it. It must also be in the original packaging.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Several types of goods are exempt from being returned. Perishable goods such as food, flowers, newspapers or magazines cannot be returned. We also do not accept products that are intimate or sanitary goods, hazardous materials, or flammable liquids or gases.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Additional non-returnable items:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul>\n<li>Gift cards</li>\n<li>Downloadable software products</li>\n<li>Some health and personal care items</li>\n</ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To complete your return, we require a receipt or proof of purchase.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Please do not send your purchase back to the manufacturer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are certain situations where only partial refunds are granted:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul>\n<li>Book with obvious signs of use</li>\n<li>CD, DVD, VHS tape, software, video game, cassette tape, or vinyl record that has been opened.</li>\n<li>Any item not in its original condition, is damaged or missing parts for reasons not due to our error.</li>\n<li>Any item that is returned more than 30 days after delivery</li>\n</ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<h2>Refunds</h2>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once your return is received and inspected, we will send you an email to notify you that we have received your returned item. We will also notify you of the approval or rejection of your refund.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are approved, then your refund will be processed, and a credit will automatically be applied to your credit card or original method of payment, within a certain amount of days.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<b>Late or missing refunds</b>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you haven’t received a refund yet, first check your bank account again.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then contact your credit card company, it may take some time before your refund is officially posted.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next contact your bank. There is often some processing time before a refund is posted.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you’ve done all of this and you still have not received your refund yet, please contact us at {email address}.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<b>Sale items</b>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Only regular priced items may be refunded. Sale items cannot be refunded.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<h2>Exchanges</h2>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We only replace items if they are defective or damaged. If you need to exchange it for the same item, send us an email at {email address} and send your item to: {physical address}.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<h2>Gifts</h2>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If the item was marked as a gift when purchased and shipped directly to you, you’ll receive a gift credit for the value of your return. Once the returned item is received, a gift certificate will be mailed to you.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If the item wasn’t marked as a gift when purchased, or the gift giver had the order shipped to themselves to give to you later, we will send a refund to the gift giver and they will find out about your return.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<h2>Shipping returns</h2>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To return your product, you should mail your product to: {physical address}.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You will be responsible for paying for your own shipping costs for returning your item. Shipping costs are non-refundable. If you receive a refund, the cost of return shipping will be deducted from your refund.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Depending on where you live, the time it may take for your exchanged product to reach you may vary.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are returning more expensive items, you may consider using a trackable shipping service or purchasing shipping insurance. We don’t guarantee that we will receive your returned item.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<h2>Need help?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Contact us at {email} for questions related to refunds and returns.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Refund and Returns Policy','','draft','closed','closed','','refund_returns','','','2023-07-23 21:39:44','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?page_id=12',0,'page','',0),(31,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:06','2023-07-23 21:52:06','This classic fourth issue of Monk was randomly discovered by an LA Times reporter, and the rest is history. The world took notice!In our trusty Ford Econoline, we hightailed it out of San Diego for the vortexes of Sedona, where, in the shadow of Bell Rock, The Monks joined the Harmonic Convergence, the world’s first synchronized global peace meditation spawned by vague, unverified ancient Mayan prophesies. We discover Hot Apple Pi, the global New Age elite, the treacherous art of cliff-jumping, and the joys of homemade, campground Space Monk waffles, as Jim channels Barbie, Mike perfects his patented leek-mushroom soup, and we both receive some invaluable advice from an unlikely source: “Stay Below the Radar!”','Episode 4: Sedona','','publish','open','closed','','issue-four-sedona','','','2023-09-21 03:50:22','2023-09-21 03:50:22','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=31',0,'product','',0),(32,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:06','2023-07-23 21:52:06','Van life proves to be immensely challenging during our first cold weather sojourn to the daunting Rocky Mountains. Gobsmacked by our barefoot ectomorph starvation look, the communal residents of Norwood’s Re-enchantment Lodge mistakenly invite us in for the season. High on Auro Trading herbs and Vitasoy (thank you, Hilton Tsui!), we eventually navigate our ice encrusted Econoline to the Oracle of Aspen and ask, “What’s the difference between angels and ETs?” His reply: “Dont ask me, ask the pendulum.”Mountain music, sorcerers, and a major brake failure down an icy highway to Durango add to the chills and thrills.','Episode 5: Colorado','','publish','open','closed','','issue-five-colorado','','','2023-09-21 03:51:29','2023-09-21 03:51:29','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=32',0,'product','',0),(33,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:06','2023-07-23 21:52:06','On our way to meet the Omaha in-laws, our beloved Econoline chugs its final mile. Thanks to an assist from Jim’s dermatologist dad––a Great Depression Monk from Tyndall, SD––we drive away in our slightly used, and, as we quickly learn, hugely defective, monastery-on-wheels, the 1986, twenty-six-foot Fleetwood Bounder “Monkmobile.” Now officially “motor-homeboys,” we head south for warmer climes, drifting into a “Lonestar State of Mind” courtesy of Lady Bird Johnson and folkabilly sensation Nanci Griffith. After stops in Dallas to visit “the grassy knoll,” and Corpus Christi just as the Berlin Wall falls, our loyal subscriber, Cheryl Wagner, arrives with a wallet full of credit cards and promptly fills up the giant “Bounder” gas tank, allowing us to amble up the Rio Grande to Big Bend National Park, from where we embark upon a dangerous crossing into Boquillas, Mexico in a leaky rowboat. Nurse makes a surprise reincarnation, as we hotly debate whether we are, in fact, entering a New Ice Age. Texas has still not recovered.','Episode 6: Texas','','publish','open','closed','','issue-six-texas','','','2023-09-21 03:50:44','2023-09-21 03:50:44','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=33',0,'product','',0),(34,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:07','2023-07-23 21:52:07','Dogged by late night UFOs while trekking through the irradiated landscape of White Sands and Roswell, The Monks arrive in “Fanta Say,” where they quickly master the Sikh art of turban wrapping, marvel at the abundance of ristras, turquoise, and adobes, as we encounter our displaced “Dolphfriends,” with a guest appearance from Chuck “Yma Sumac Kastner. Skirting past the Santa Fe Opera, we make camp in the Rio Grande Gorge, seeking out the avatar of Ojo Sarco, Girl Doggie, and her loyal companion, Girl Carol, as we discover the stunning, majestic terrain of the Land of Enchantment.','Episode 7: Santa Fe','','publish','open','closed','','issue-seven-santa-fe','','','2023-09-21 03:49:56','2023-09-21 03:49:56','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=34',0,'product','',0),(35,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:07','2023-07-23 21:52:07','Slow down. Slow wayyyyyyy down. After a detour through Amarillo to visit Stanley Marsh III’s Cadillac Ranch, we enter The O-Zone, The Ozarks, that is, where the tall thin monk, aka Arkansas Slim, was born. Granny’s on the back porch rocker modeling the fine art of visitin’, as blackberry cobbler, homemade biscuits and gravy, and iced tea reign supreme. The Monks reenact “The Crisis at Central High,” Nurse reincarnates as Her Holiness the Great Dolly Lama, and the soy goys take on the cowboys. Toad Suck, the House of BOB, Christ of the Ozarks, Mt. Ida Crystals and the King of the South round out the journey before a low center of gravity keeps us from sliding off the road into oblivion.','Episode 8: The Ozarks','','publish','open','closed','','issue-eight-the-ozarks','','','2023-09-21 03:49:33','2023-09-21 03:49:33','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=35',0,'product','',0),(36,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:07','2023-07-23 21:52:07','The Monks blow in from “Missoura” and land in “New Yawk’s” Thompson Square Park for a crash course in urban camping, surrounded by crack connoisseurs, squeegee entrepreneurs, ATM greeters, and a genuine bonfire of the insanities before retreating to a riot at the Tenth Street Baths. We venture Deep Inside Annie Sprinkle, while contending with daily break-ins, a chance encounter with Woody Allen, and the search for the perfect phone booth. We tap out in a Chelsea high-rise and regroup before hitting the Mars, the Limelight, and the bowels of Port Authority. With “tits on head,” Manhattan gets Monked','Episode 9: New York','','publish','open','closed','','issue-nine-monks-invade-new-york','','','2023-09-21 03:48:53','2023-09-21 03:48:53','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=36',0,'product','',0),(37,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:07','2023-07-23 21:52:07','The Tall One turns 40 and travels that long and blinding road from Woodstock to Wigstock. A full-blown crisis ensues, as The Monks are forced to decamp to toxic North Bergen, “New Joisey,” before losing our shit on the Coney Island Cyclone and getting swept off our feet at the Mermaid Parade. Thankfully, a random Greenpeace encounter pulls us toward Atlantic City followed by a welcome respite at another March on Washington, before the magnetic pull of Lady Bunny’s Wigstock draws us back into the Manhattan mix. The Feast of St. Francis center us back in our hearts, as Michael suffers four decades of painfully personal flashbacks. There’s no place like roam.','Episode 10: Midlife Crisis','','publish','open','closed','','issue-ten-michaels-midlife-crisis','','','2023-09-21 03:47:47','2023-09-21 03:47:47','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=37',0,'product','',0),(38,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:07','2023-07-23 21:52:07','Get out the sunblock. The Monks leave the clutches of Soho’s meat market and travel south along the gator trail in search of Florida gold . . . sunshine, that is. Sharks, surf, and South Beach attitude dominate in the Art Deco capital of the world. We start our voyage at the Bay of Wigs in Little Havana, feasting on fried plantains and arroz con pollo, making fatal decisions on the male bikini (do you wear it up or down?), while falling under Ocean Drive’s spell of feathers and glitter. Flamingoes figure prominently on Route One to The Keys, where the world’s trickiest escape artist slips out of a tight fit, a renegade alligator lodges under Bounder, and Glades’ mosquitoes overstay their welcome forcing us to burn rubber up the Gulf for the Weeki Wachee Mermaid Show. A date with destiny we won’t forget.','Episode 11: Florida','','publish','open','closed','','issue-eleven-from-soho-to-soflo','','','2023-09-21 03:46:32','2023-09-21 03:46:32','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=38',0,'product','',0),(39,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:08','2023-07-23 21:52:08','The Monks head out in search of Queen Anne. But Queen Anne is not “search.” In a twisted odyssey through the strange, eerie subcultures of Vacationland USA, the Monks finally learn the meaning of that old Buddhist trope, “If you see Queen Anne on the road, kill her.” Lobster traps rise out of fog banks, as we pass carloads of Rubenesque, spandex-wearing, Maine-iacs piloting a disproportionate number of Dodge Coronets. Bouncing over frost heaves in the road, The Monks finally arrive at the picture perfection of Mt. Desert Island. The area Blue Bloods dodge gender-confused moose, we take icy Fall swims in Southwest Harbor, and Aide blithely saunters off into Stephen King’s <i>Pet Sematary</i>.','Episode 12: Maine','','publish','open','closed','','issue-twelve-queen-anne-is-maine','','','2023-09-21 03:46:07','2023-09-21 03:46:07','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=39',0,'product','',0),(40,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:08','2023-07-23 21:52:08','News flash: Boston is NOT New York. Dolly Lama throws a curve ball sending The Monks on a wild chase across Beantown, combing the cobblestone for clues. Is she “the money cat or an imposter?” From bag ladies to Harvard’s elite, the Hilltop Steak House to the Beacon Hill State House, we eat our way through the best diners in America and up the Saugus Trail in hot <i>purrrr</i>-suit of an answer. Athenaeum chaos rules until Deadhead Governor Bill Weld','Episode 13: Boston','','publish','open','closed','','issue-thirteen-boston','','','2023-09-21 03:43:27','2023-09-21 03:43:27','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=40',0,'product','',0),(41,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:08','2023-07-23 21:52:08','Grunge is dead and we’re not going to cry. <i>The New York Times</i><i>Vogue</i> discover flannel, just as the Monks nail the lid on the coffin. But wait . . . the spirit of Seattle lives on. The Monks arrive in The Emerald City and slip into a rain warp, with all roads leading to Capital Hill and all nights ending at the Doghouse. The year feels like 1972, but it’s 1992, and the mood is long hair and geoducks, Java Jive, Hat and Boots, and Twin Teepees, with late night dips at Green Lake. Espresso flows like lava, as the Moleman gives a revealing tour of the Pioneer Square underground leading to the force behind Grunge itself. The Seattle issue features Artis the Spoonman, Dave Grohl, and a rare interview with Kurt Cobain in the last Nirvana feature you’ll ever need to read.','Episode 14: Seattle','','publish','open','closed','','issue-fourteen-seattle-sucks-geoducks','','','2023-09-21 03:45:11','2023-09-21 03:45:11','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=41',0,'product','',0),(42,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:08','2023-07-23 21:52:08','Quiet on the set! Surf’s up and the cameras are rolling as The Monks hit the “City of Angles” with stardom on the brain. Bag ladies with big lips, Monks named Mu, and the nudists of Elysium Fields spawn an endless stream of self -promotion as a cast of thousands crash through the Monk dashboard screen. We take of tour of the LAPD shooting range with the custodian of Chicken Boy, and post-riot tour of South Central with Vaginal Cream Davis, a male blacktress in heels. We hang with Spike Jonze and X, and the Devo-riffing Del Rubio Triples, the campiest road act to ever hit Hollywood. Our lady of the transit opera takes us from Malibu to Santa Monica, omnipresent helicopters circle the Bradbury Building, as the Monks crash the Oscars inflicting mass confusion on the red carpet. Jim’s “33 Reasons Why We Love L.A.” is shared around the world. We may have left our hearts in San Francisco, but LA let us know this is where we belong.','Episode 15: Los Angeles','','publish','open','closed','','issue-fifteen-greetings-from-los-angeles','','','2023-09-21 03:44:49','2023-09-21 03:44:49','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=42',0,'product','',1),(43,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:08','2023-07-23 21:52:08','After eight years away, The Monks make their “Great Return” to the cultural petri dish where it all started, San Francisco. We come to a roaring stop at a South of Market RV park and get a sneak peak of the dawning Internet Age, as we hobnob with the creators of Wired, Mondo 2000, and Craig’s List. Relentlessly pursued by a meter maid from hell, the Monkmobile is a roaming target for break-ins in Hayes Valley, as we discover freezers full of frozen cats, owls and mice, pierced and tattooed drag queens, snow domes, blood and guts, broken glass and late-night quarter-pounders. Mike’s futile quest to just have a Normal Day goes unrewarded, as we encounter the last of Weird San Francisco before the Technorati ate its soul.','Episode 16: San Francisco','','publish','open','closed','','issue-sixteen-freakin-in-frisco','','','2023-09-21 03:44:24','2023-09-21 03:44:24','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=43',0,'product','',0),(44,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:08','2023-07-23 21:52:08','In a town as bird-crazy and politically correct as Portland, it came as no surprise that the addictive substance of choice was a holistic edible bird seed. The Portland scene was raw. In Bridgetown, locals don’t tan, they rust. And they don’t carry umbrellas. Here, pot is king, beer is micro-brewed, and gutter punks are treated like sacred cows. High on millet, The Monks enter the mandala of Migrating Hagfish, the Mystery Hole, and the biblical perversion of the Religious Right. We are granted audiences with “The Emperor, Gus Van Sant, and his lieutenant, The Man, while the Road Babes, smelling of Medford innocence and Harvard legacy, chase us down the highway to the Da Kind Good Bob, folkloric father figure to a generation of Protean youth in need of a home. We roam the Far Side of Highway 97, entering deep into the frump, funk, and fun capital of America. Kurt Cobain was wrong: Portland isn’t just grunge. It’s mold.','Episode 17: Portland','','publish','open','closed','','issue-seventeen-portland-kicks-butt','','','2023-09-21 03:43:54','2023-09-21 03:43:54','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=44',0,'product','',0),(45,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:09','2023-07-23 21:52:09','Hunter S. Thompson––move over. There’s a new breed of mutant nomad stalking Sin City. More outrageous, mind-bending adventure per square inch than any travelogue about the town. And we did it without drugs. Welcome to Second Chance City. Vegas, baby. From showgirls to bikers, whores to a thousand cops in tennis shoes, The Monks seek out the Old West holdouts, brave the Klondike buffet, cruise the strip, land in greasy motels, and get terrorized by Mob Bob and Two-Fisted Jake. Then, far from Clark County, the Monks prove their early BURNER cred (1994) with a stopover in Black Rock City before the Silicon Valley and influencer hoards descended. Yes, a live ammo drive-by shooting range, nighttime art car races, mud-caked hot springs, an existentialist boxing match, and a bold, Monk-led attempt to live broadcast from The Burn. The desert’s a stage and we are all players.','Episode 18: Nevada','','publish','open','closed','','issue-eighteen-planet-nevada','','','2023-09-21 03:42:54','2023-09-21 03:42:54','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=45',0,'product','',0),(46,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:09','2023-07-23 21:52:09','We couldn’t get enough of the Big Apple. The Monkmobile suffers a fatal breakdown as she limps into The Naked City for a final tour. Raw from 200,000 plus miles under our feeble fan belt, we land at Joe’s Truck Repair, camp in Williamsburg (pre-hipster), suffer through a summer heatwave (global warming having replaced the coming Ice Age as the hypochrondial obsession du jour), barbecue in the shadow of The Twin Towers (pre-9/11), and cruise the seedy underbelly of Times Square (pre-Disneyfication). Searching for bull penis in Chinatown, we cruise the last vestiges of authentic New York, including Princess Pamela’s fried chicken, Yonah Schimmel’s Knishes, Katz’s Deli, Hotel Chelsea, the African American Wax Museum, and Fresh Kills Dump (yes, really). We land afternoons with <span style=\"font-family: Arial Unicode MS, serif;\"><span lang=\"it-IT\">Quentin Crisp, </span></span><span style=\"font-family: Arial Unicode MS, serif;\"><span lang=\"en-US\">the Woman with a Beard, Gene Pool, and a final stop at The Doll Hospital. Goodbye squeegee people, St. Mark’s Place, and CBGBs. As gentrification takes hold, The Monks close the curtain on the glory days of New York and twelve years on the road.</span></span>','Episode 19: New York part two','','publish','open','closed','','issue-nineteen-new-york','','','2023-09-21 03:48:23','2023-09-21 03:48:23','',0,'http://monkmagazine.test/?post_type=product&#038;p=46',0,'product','',0),(47,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:09','2023-07-23 21:52:09','','EP4front-big.jpg','','inherit','open','closed','','ep4front-big-jpg','','','2023-07-23 21:52:09','2023-07-23 21:52:09','',31,'http://monkmagazine.test/app/uploads/2023/07/EP4front-big.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(48,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:10','2023-07-23 21:52:10','','EP4back-big-1.jpg','','inherit','open','closed','','ep4back-big-1-jpg','','','2023-07-23 21:52:10','2023-07-23 21:52:10','',31,'http://monkmagazine.test/app/uploads/2023/07/EP4back-big-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(49,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:10','2023-07-23 21:52:10','','EP5front-big-1.jpg','','inherit','open','closed','','ep5front-big-1-jpg','','','2023-07-23 21:52:10','2023-07-23 21:52:10','',32,'http://monkmagazine.test/app/uploads/2023/07/EP5front-big-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(50,1,'2023-07-23 21:52:11','2023-07-23 21:52:11','','EP5back-big.jpg','','inherit','open','close